          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>For a separated simplicial scheme (or separated simplicial algebraic space) <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X^\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, we will have to consider diagrams

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2494</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.3.1.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.3.1.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>8.3.1.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.3.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:embedded-tex hash="385923405a7e2f06d2faa5b3b9efa8e5"><fr:embedded-tex-preamble><![CDATA[
    \usepackage {amsmath}
    \usepackage {amssymb}
    \usepackage {tikz-cd}
  ]]></fr:embedded-tex-preamble><fr:embedded-tex-body><![CDATA[\begin {tikzcd}
        X_\bullet 
          \ar [r,hook,"j"]
          \ar [d,swap,"p"]
        & \overline {Z}_\bullet 
      \\X_\bullet 
        && (8.3.1.1)
      \end {tikzcd}]]></fr:embedded-tex-body></fr:embedded-tex>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    of simplicial schemes satisfying:
    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
        The morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex> is an open immersion with dense image; <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {Z}_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is proper.
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
        The evident morphisms <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Z_n\to (\operatorname {cosq}_{n-1}^{X_\bullet }\operatorname {sq}_{n-1}Z_\bullet )_n]]></fr:tex> are proper and surjective.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
            <fr:p>For reduced <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {Z}_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, we can consider <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex> as a simplicial object in the category <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {C}]]></fr:tex> of pairs <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(Y,\overline {Y})]]></fr:tex> consisting of a proper reduced scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {Y}]]></fr:tex> and a dense (Zariski) open <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {Y}]]></fr:tex>.
    The category <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {C}]]></fr:tex> satisfies <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.4.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.4.1.xml" number="6.2.4.1" />, which allows us to apply the analogue of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.4" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.4.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="6.2.4" />.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
